<div class="lightblock" style="margin: 6em 2em;">
<div class="cheadbg"><div class="customhead">• Description </div></div>
<center>'''Ferronix Sillicate''' is designated as the 70<sup>th</sup> object of the Backrooms.</center><br>{{Blurimage|align=right|file=Ferronix Sillicate.png|caption=An image of a large Ferronix Sillicate formation under direct illumination.}}
'''Ferronix Silicate,''' otherwise chemically abbreviated as '''Fe<sub>2</sub>NxSiO<sub>6</sub>''', is a dense, and inorganic crystal. It maintains a dark, and heavily muted brown coloration with subtle luminescent veins proliferating upon its surface. It commonly grows in forms of irregular hexagonal prisms or fragmented shards with jagged, and sharp edges. The texture of its surface varies from smooth, and glassy to coarse, and granular. However, they consistently reflect light in a muted, and green oily gleam.

When observed in a dimly-lit environment, light yellow or reddish lines can be seen running through the crystal, and they appear to be concentrated within internal boundaries and fracture zones. These lines are not seen perpectually static; their brightness intensity and hue constantly fluctuates slightly from time to time without a discernable pattern. Under complete direct illumination, the crystal becomes largely opaque and its aforementioned lines become invisible, although thin fragments may appear translucent near their edges.

'''Ferronix Sillicate''' feels heavier than what is expected of its size, which led chemists to hypothesized its internal composition is tightly packed. It remains unbroken under moderate pressure but can crack then fracture abruptly under sufficient force. Recently broken '''Ferronix Sillicate''' pieces feature bright luminescent veins before eventually abating.

'''Ferronix Silicate''' is generally stable under normal environmental conditions; it shows no visible reaction to air or moisture. However, when put within elevated temperatures for a prolonged amount of time, it may show slight discoloration, and dimming of its aforementioned lines glow.
</div>
<div class="lightblock" style="margin: 6em 2em;">
<div class="cheadbg"><div class="customhead">• Usage </div></div>
'''Ferronix Silicate''' is mainly utilized as a source of producing raw electricity. The crystal does not require pre-existing electrical input to produce current; instead, electricity is generated by precise physical interactions occurring between specific conductive points present within the crystal structure itself. These points, commonly known as “nodes,” are naturally distributed throughout the compound in strange yet partially repeated arrangements.

When two active nodes are simultaneously connected by a conductive material, localized charge displacement occurs within the crystal, which results in the immediate generation of electrical current. Output from a single shard is typically weak and unstable; frequently in forms of sparks, fluctuating voltage, or rapid discharge. Pressure, vibration, sudden thermal fluctuations, and synchronized contact across multiple nodes amplify this effect to varying extents.

Researches has given that '''Ferronix Silicate''' becomes substantially more efficient when bonded with multiple crystals together in symmetrical arrangements. Configurations such as triangular, hexagonal, or concentric layouts appear to stabilize internal charge resonance between individual shards, which allow energy production to remain continuous instead of sporadic. Improper arrangements generally produce either inefficiently low output or destructive discharges with chances of fracturing the entire structure. Larger bonded ones produce significantly greater electricity due to the synchronization of node activity across the crystal network. The symmetry of the arrangement is considered essential; even minor inconsistencies can disrupt resonance patterns, and reduce efficiency.

Many organized engineer groups; mostly such as [[A.D.F.]], [[Architect Industries]], etc.; seldom integrate '''Ferronix Silicate''' into the infrastructure of their machinaries. Small bonded ones are frequently utilized as substitutes for batteries or fuel-powered generators, particularly in where conventional energy sources are scarce. Larger ones have been used to power lighting systems, communication equipment, mechanical doors, water filtration devices, and defensive tools.


