|-| Ferronix Lantern=
=== 1. Ferronix Lantern ===
==== Recipe ====
===== Required Materials =====
<ul>
<li>'''Ferronix''' shard ×1</li>
<li>Glass container ×1</li>
<li>Thin copper wiring ×2</li>
<li>Small light bulb or filament ×1</li>
<li>Metal cap ×1</li>
<li>Clothe or rubber strip ×1</li>
</ul>

===== Process Steps =====
<div style="transform: translateX(-10px);>
<ol>
<li>Inspect the '''Ferronix''' shard and try to locate two active nodes. These usually appear as glowing spots or thin luminous lines along the crystal surface.</li>
<li>Wrap one copper wire around one of the nodes and another wire around the other node. Make sure to tightly secure both wires and do not make them contact each other directly.</li>
<li>Attach the ends of both wires to the small light bulb or filament. Once connected successfully and correctly, the filament may briefly start to flicker.</li>
<li>Carefully place the '''Ferronix''' shard and wiring configuration inside the glass container. Put the bulb near the upper section so the light spreads evenly.</li>
<li>Seal the container using the metal cap or lid while leaving small openings for heat ventilation. Make sure the internal components remain stable and do not move excessively.</li>
<li>Wrap the exterior grip area with rubber or cloth to reduce accidental electrical discharge and to improve handling comfort.</li>
</ol>
</div>

==== Machanism/Usage ====
The lantern operates through the natural electrical generation properties of '''Ferronix Silicate'''. The crystal continuously produces small electrical fluctuations between active nodes, and the copper wiring directs this current into the filament, causing it to emit light. Movement, pressure, and environmental vibration slightly brighten the lantern glow while being carried. Stable wiring and proper node alignment are essential, as poor connections may result flickering or complete failure.

|-| Ferronix Discharger=
=== 2. Ferronix Discharger ===
==== Required Materials ====
<ul>
<li>'''Ferronix''' Shard ×2</li>
<li>Hollow Metal Pipe ×1</li>
<li>Copper Wiring ×3</li>
<li>Conductive Prongs ×2</li>
<li>Rubber Grip ×1</li>
<li>Connective Resin or Adhesive ×1</li>
</ul>

==== Process Steps ====
<div style="transform: translateX(-10px);>
<ol>
<li>Clean the inside of the hollow metal pipe with enough space for both '''Ferronix''' shards.</li>
<li>Place the two '''Ferronix''' shards facing one another inside the pipe. Their active nodes should be aligned symmetrically for stable resonance.</li>
<li>Use copper wiring to connect the active nodes of both shards together. Make sure the wires are tightly secured and evenly arranged to avoid unstable discharge.</li>
<li>Attach the conductive prongs to the exposed wire terminals near the front end of the rod. These prongs will act as the discharge point for electrical output.</li>
<li>Apply connective resin or adhesive around the shards and wiring to prevent movement inside the pipe. Allow the configuration to fully stabilize before use.</li>
<li>Wrap the lower handle section with rubber insulation to prevent it from accidentally discharging the electricity to the user.</li>
</ol></div>

==== Machanism/Usage ====
The '''Ferronix Discharger''' is primarily used as a close-range electrical defensive weapon. It functions through resonance generated between the two '''Ferronix''' shards. When aligned correctly, the crystals continuously create electrical charge differences between their active nodes. This charge remains relatively stable until physical contact or sudden pressure disrupts the resonance balance.

Upon striking or touching a surface, the stored electrical imbalance rapidly redirects toward the conductive prongs, and shocks the contacted material. Proper symmetry between both crystals is essential, as uneven positioning may destabilize resonance and cause uncontrolled discharge inside the rod itself.

|-| Ferronix Signal Receiver=
=== 3. Ferronix Signal Receiver ===
==== Required Materials ====
<ul>
<li>'''Ferronix''' Shard ×1</li>
<li>Salvaged Radio Speaker ×1</li>
<li>Fine Copper Coil ×1</li>
<li>Metal Housing ×1</li>
<li>Small Switch ×1</li>
<li>Fasteners or Screws ×Several</li>
</ul>

==== Process Steps ====
<div style="transform: translateX(-10px);>
<ol>
<li>Open the metal housing and clear enough internal space for the speaker, '''Ferronix''' fragment, and wiring.</li>
<li>Carefully wrap the fine copper coil around the '''Ferronix''' fragment. Leave both ends of the coil exposed for connection.</li>
<li>Secure the speaker inside the housing near the front openings so sound can travel outward clearly.</li>
<li>Attach the ends of the copper coil to the speaker assembly. Install the switch between the connections so the device can be activated and deactivated safely.</li>
<li>Use screws or fasteners to keep the '''Ferronix''' fragment and wiring stable inside the housing. Loose components may interfere with signal clarity.</li>
<li>Close the housing while keeping small openings for sound output and airflow</li>
</ol>
</div>

==== Machanism/Usage ====
The '''Ferronix Signal Receiver''' is used to detect and convert nearby electromagnetic signals into audible sound. Unlike normal radios, the device does not rely entirely on standard electronic circuitry. Instead, the '''Ferronix''' fragment reacts directly to surrounding electrical disturbances and radio frequencies. When active, the crystal naturally produces small electrical fluctuations inside the copper coil wrapped around it. Nearby signals disturb these fluctuations, which cause changes in electrical behavior of the crystal. The speaker then converts these changes into sound. In other simpler words, the '''Ferronix''' fragment plays a role as a highly sensitive signal detector. Invisible radio waves and electrical activity in the environment slightly disturb the crystal, and the device translates those disturbances into noises, voices, or transmissions.

Because of its unusual sensitivity, the '''Ferronix Signal Receiver''' may occasionally detect signals beyond ordinary radio broadcasts; including unidentified transmissions, mechanical interference, or other audio phenomena.
